{"title_page": "Adelina Sotnikova", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox figure skater\n|name= Adelina Sotnikova\n|native_name = \u0410\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\n|native_name_lang = ru\n|image= Adelina Sotnikova Sochi Medal Ceremony 05 (cropped).jpg\n|imagesize=240px\n|caption= Sotnikova at the 2014 Sochi Winter Olympics podium\n|fullname= Adelina Dmitriyevna Sotnikova\n|country= [[Russia]]\n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|df=yes|1996|7|1}}\n|birth_place = [[Moscow]], Russia\n|residence= Moscow, Russia\n|height= {{height|m=1.63|precision=0}}\n|coach= [[Evgeni Plushenko]]\n|formercoach= [[Elena Vodorezova|Elena Vodorezova (Buianova)]]\n|choreographer=[[Emanuel Sandhu]]\n|formerchoreographer= [[Tatiana Tarasova]], [[Peter Tchernyshev]], Irina Tagaeva\n|skating club = [[CSKA Moscow]]\n|beganskating = 2000\n|retired = 2 March 2020\n|worldranking = '''103''' (''[[2017\u201318 ISU World Standings and Season's World Ranking|2017\u201318]]'') <br> '''79''' (''[[2016\u201317 ISU World Standings and Season's World Ranking|2016\u201317]]'') <br> '''19''' (''[[2015\u201316 ISU World Standings and Season's World Ranking|2015\u201316]]'') <br> '''9''' (''[[2014\u201315 ISU World Standings and Season's World Ranking|2014\u201315]]'') <br> '''4''' (''[[2013\u201314 ISU World Standings and Season's World Ranking|2013\u201314]]'') <br> '''9''' (''[[2012\u201313 ISU World Standings and Season's World Ranking|2012\u201313]]'') <br> '''14''' (''[[2011\u201312 ISU World Standings and Season's World Ranking|2011\u201312]]'') <br> '''37''' (''[[2010\u201311 ISU World Standings and Season's World Ranking|2010\u201311]]'')\n|pbrankings = 24 (2015\u201316) \n'''1''' (''[[2013\u20132014 figure skating season|2013\u20132014]]'')<ref name=1314ts/> <br>'''5''' (''[[2012\u20132013 figure skating season|2012\u20132013]]'')<ref name=1213ts/><br>'''13''' (''[[2011\u20132012 figure skating season|2011\u20132012]]'')<ref name=1112ts/><br>'''9''' (''[[2010\u20132011 figure skating season|2010\u20132011]]'')<ref name=1011ts/>\n|combined total= 224.59\n|combined date= [[Figure skating at the 2014 Winter Olympics \u2013 Ladies' singles|2014 Winter Olympics]]\n|SP score= 75.57\n|SP date= [[2015 Mordovian Ornament]]\n|FS score= 149.95\n|FS date= [[Figure skating at the 2014 Winter Olympics \u2013 Ladies' singles|2014 Winter Olympics]]\n|show-medals = yes\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalCountry | {{RUS}} }}\n{{MedalSport | [[Figure skating]]: [[Single skating|Ladies' singles]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[List of figure skating competitions|International competitions]]}}\n{{MedalCount\n|[[List of Olympic medalists in figure skating|Olympic Games]]|1|0|0\n|[[European Figure Skating Championships|European Championships]]|0|2|0\n|[[Figure skating at the Youth Olympic Games|Winter Youth Olympics]]|0|1|0\n|[[World Junior Figure Skating Championships|World Junior Championships]]|1|0|1\n|[[ISU Junior Grand Prix Final|Junior Grand Prix Final]]|1|0|0\n|'''Total'''|'''3'''|'''3'''|'''1'''\n}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Figure skating at the Winter Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Figure skating at the 2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Sochi]]|[[Figure skating at the 2014 Winter Olympics \u2013 Ladies' singles|Ladies' singles]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Figure Skating Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2013 European Figure Skating Championships|2013 Zagreb]]|Ladies' singles}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 European Figure Skating Championships|2014 Budapest]]|Ladies' singles}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Figure skating at the Youth Olympic Games|Winter Youth Olympics]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[Figure skating at the 2012 Winter Youth Olympics|2012 Innsbruck]] | Ladies' singles}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Junior Figure Skating Championships|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2011 World Junior Figure Skating Championships|2011 Gangneung]]|Ladies' singles}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2012 World Junior Figure Skating Championships|2012 Minsk]]|Ladies' singles}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[ISU Junior Grand Prix Final|Junior Grand Prix Final]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2010\u201311 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2010\u201311 Beijing]]|Ladies' singles}}\n}}\n'''Adelina Dmitriyevna Sotnikova''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0410\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0301\u043d\u0430 \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0301\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u0301\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430}} {{IPA-ru|\u0250d\u02b2\u026a\u02c8l\u02b2in\u0259 \u02c8sot\u02b2n\u02b2\u026ak\u0259v\u0259|}}; born 1 July 1996) is a retired Russian [[Figure skating|figure skater]]. She is the [[Figure skating at the 2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Olympic champion]], a two-time [[European Figure Skating Championships|Europeans]] silver medalist (2012, 2013), a two-time [[Rostelecom Cup]] bronze medalist (2011, 2015), and a four-time [[Russian Figure Skating Championships|Russian national]] champion (2009, 2011, 2012, 2014).\n\nOn the junior level, she is the [[Figure skating at the Youth Olympic Games|2012 Youth Olympic silver medalist]], the 2011 [[World Junior Figure Skating Championships|Junior World]] champion, the 2010 [[ISU Junior Grand Prix Final|Junior Grand Prix Final]] champion, and the 2009 [[Russian Figure Skating Championships|Russian junior national]] champion.\n\nSotnikova stopped competing after the 2015\u20132016 season. She announced her retirement on 1 March 2020.<ref>[https://tass.ru/sport/7874845 \u0410\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043e \u0437\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0440\u044b]. tass.ru (2 March 2020)</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAdelina Sotnikova began skating at the age of four at the ''Yuzhny'' [[ice rink]] near her home in Moscow.<ref name=girlpower/><ref name=ontrack/><ref name=sovs1208/> Taught by Anna Patrikeeva until the age of seven,<ref name=MN130423/><ref name=SD1404/> she then began training at [[CSKA Moscow|CSKA]] which is further away from her home.<ref name=ontrack/> She began working with coach [[Elena Vodorezova|Elena Buianova (Vodorezova)]] a year later.<ref name=sovs1208/>\n\nDuring the 2008\u20132009 season, Sotnikova debuted at the senior level at the [[2009 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2009 Russian Nationals]] and won the gold medal at the age of 12.<ref name=sovs1208/><ref name =gs09rusnats/> One month later she also won the [[2009 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2009 Russian Junior Championships]].<ref name = goldsk09rusjnats/>\n\nSotnikova was ineligible to compete on the Junior Grand Prix circuit during the 2009\u20132010 season because [[International Skating Union]] rules require that skaters turn 13 before 1 July in their place of birth \u2013 she was born a few hours into 1 July in Moscow.<ref name=se1210/> Sotnikova's mother told her that she was born a month prematurely anyway.<ref name=se1210/> She struggled with a growth spurt and dropped to fourth at Russian senior nationals and sixth in the junior event.\n\n===2010\u20132011 season===\n[[File:Grand Prix Final 2010 \u2013 Juniors \u2013 Ladies.jpg|left|thumb|250px|Sotnikova with medalists [[Elizaveta Tuktamysheva]] and [[Li Zijun]] at the [[2010\u201311 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2010\u201311 JGP Final]]]]Sotnikova made her junior Grand Prix debut during the [[2010\u20132011 figure skating season|2010\u20132011 season]]. She won gold medals in Austria and the U.K. and qualified for the [[2010\u20132011 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2010 Junior Grand Prix Final]] where she won the title.<ref name =gsjungpf/>\nAt the [[2011 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2011 Russian Championships]], she placed second in the short program and first in the long, to win her second national title.<ref name=gs11rusnats/> She was assigned to the [[2011 World Junior Figure Skating Championships|World Junior Championships]] where she won the gold medal ahead of teammate [[Elizaveta Tuktamysheva]].<ref name=gs11junworldsp/><ref name=gs11junworldfp/>\n\n===2011\u20132012 season===\nAccording to ISU age rules, Sotnikova was eligible for the [[2011\u201312 ISU Grand Prix of Figure Skating|senior Grand Prix]] circuit during the [[2011\u20132012 figure skating season|2011\u20132012 season]], although not for senior ISU Championships. She was assigned to two Grand Prix events, the [[2011 Cup of China]] and [[2011 Rostelecom Cup]]. She intended to begin her season at the [[2011 Ondrej Nepela Memorial]] but withdrew after a leg injury caused her to miss a month of off-season training.<ref name=in1109/> She won the bronze medal at Cup of China<ref name=gs11coclp/> and at Rostelecom Cup, to become the first alternate for the ladies' event at the [[2011\u20132012 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|Grand Prix Final]].\n\nSotnikova then competed at the [[2011 Golden Spin of Zagreb]] and won the gold medal. At the [[2012 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2012 Russian Championships]], she placed first in the short program and second in the long program, to win her third national title. She then competed at the [[Figure skating at the 2012 Winter Youth Olympics|2012 Youth Olympic Games]] and won the silver medal. At the [[2012 World Junior Figure Skating Championships|2012 World Junior Championships]], she won the bronze medal behind teammate [[Yulia Lipnitskaya]] and U.S. skater [[Gracie Gold]].<ref name=rs120308/> Sotnikova was named in the Russian team for [[2012 ISU World Team Trophy in Figure Skating|2012 ISU World Team Trophy]]. She finished 4th overall and posted a season's best in her free skate of 113.57 points.\n\n===2012\u20132013 season===\nSotnikova started her season with a silver medal at the [[2012 Nebelhorn Trophy]]. Her first GP event of the season was the [[2012 Skate America]].<ref name=gs121017/> In the free skate, Sotnikova's 3Lo-2T-2Lo jump combination received no points because it was deemed an invalid element. She won the bronze medal overall behind Americans [[Christina Gao]] and gold medalist [[Ashley Wagner]]. At her next event, the [[2012 Rostelecom Cup]], Sotnikova finished 5th. At the [[2013 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2013 Russian Championships]], she won the bronze medal behind [[Elena Radionova]] and [[Elizaveta Tuktamysheva]]. At the [[2013 European Figure Skating Championships|2013 European Championships]], she placed first in the short program, third in the long program, and won the silver medal overall, 0.72 points behind gold medalist [[Carolina Kostner]]. Sotnikova and bronze medalist [[Elizaveta Tuktamysheva]] were Russia's first medalists in the Europeans ladies' event since [[Irina Slutskaya]] won the title in 2006.\n\nAfter Europeans, Sotnikova performed in ''Art on Ice'' in Switzerland.<ref name=absk130314/> She finished 9th in her [[2013 World Figure Skating Championships|World Championships]] debut. Appearing in her second team event, she placed fourth in ladies at the [[2013 ISU World Team Trophy in Figure Skating|2013 World Team Trophy]].<ref name=fsfr130413/> Team Russia finished 4th overall.\n\n===2013\u20132014 season===\n[[File:Cup of China 2013 \u2013 Ladies.jpg|left|thumb|258px|Sotnikova at the [[2013 Cup of China]] podium]]Sotnikova started her season competing with Team Europe at the [[Japan Open (figure skating)|2013 Japan Open]]. Her first [[2013\u201314 ISU Grand Prix of Figure Skating|2013\u201314 Grand Prix]] assignment was [[2013 Cup of China|Cup of China]]. She placed first in the short and third in the free skate, winning the silver medal ahead of [[Carolina Kostner]]. In her next event, the [[2013 Troph\u00e9e \u00c9ric Bompard]], she placed third in the short, first in the free skate, and won the silver medal behind American [[Ashley Wagner]]. The results qualified Sotnikova to her first [[2013\u201314 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|Grand Prix Final]]. At the event in [[Fukuoka]], [[Japan]], she was second in the short, placed sixth in the free, and finished 5th overall.\n\nAt the [[2014 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2014 Russian Championships]], Sotnikova placed first in the short, second in the free, and won her fourth national title, edging out [[Yulia Lipnitskaya]] for the gold. Appearing in her second [[2014 European Figure Skating Championships|European Championships]], Sotnikova placed first in the short and second in the free, taking the silver medal with an overall score of 202.36 points while Lipnitskaya won gold. She is the second Russian skater to record a score above the 200 mark in ladies' singles.\n\n====2014 Olympic Winter Games====\nThe [[Figure skating at the 2014 Winter Olympics|Figure skating at the 2014 Sochi Winter Olympics]] began with the [[Figure skating at the 2014 Winter Olympics \u2013 Team trophy|team event]]. Although Russian skating officials initially intended to assign Sotnikova and Lipnitskaya to one program each, they decided a week before the event that Lipnitskaya would skate both segments.<ref name=SD1404/><ref name=reuters140221/>\n\nSotnikova won the gold medal in the [[Figure skating at the 2014 Winter Olympics \u2013 Ladies' singles|Ladies' individual event]] with an overall score of 224.59 points, becoming one of the [[List of Olympic medalists in figure skating by age#Youngest champions|youngest]] figure skating Olympic champions. She was second behind the defending Olympic and the reigning World Champion [[Kim Yuna]] by 0.28 point after the short program, but overtook Kim by winning the free skate. This led to a [[Figure skating at the 2014 Winter Olympics \u2013 Ladies' singles#Responses|controversy on the scoring and judging]], with many perceiving Sotnikova's performances to be inferior to those of Kim.\n\nIn her three seasons skating on the senior circuit, Sotnikova had never previously won a Grand Prix event, much less medaled at a major international competition such as the World Championships or the Grand Prix Final. She had previously qualified once for the world championships as a senior, finishing ninth in the 2013 Championship, which Kim won. She is the one of two Olympic gold medalists in Ladies Single (the other being [[Magda Julin]] in 1920) not to have medaled at a World Championship before or after her Olympic win, though Julin won her gold medal at a time during which the World Chamionships were suspended due to the World War I (between 1915 and 1921).<ref name=reuters140221/><ref name=sochi2014>{{cite news | url = http://www.team-russia2014.ru/article/figur/15816.html | title = Adelina Sotnikova: I was angry that I was not included in the Team event, and said to myself \"I will get a medal in the individuals, even if I have to cheat, with dope\" | publisher = Team-Russia2014 | accessdate = 21 February 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140225094725/http://www.team-russia2014.ru/article/figur/15816.html | archive-date = 25 February 2014 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Adelina-Sotnikova-used-anger-to-win-gold/tabid/415/articleID/333158/Default.aspx |title= Adelina Sotnikova used anger to win gold |publisher= 3 News New Zealand |date= 21 February 2014 |accessdate= 22 February 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140223084422/http://www.3news.co.nz/Adelina-Sotnikova-used-anger-to-win-gold/tabid/415/articleID/333158/Default.aspx |archive-date= 23 February 2014 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=TR140221/> She was awarded the [[Order of Friendship]] on 24 February 2014.<ref>{{cite news|date=24 February 2014 |title=Russia's Olympic athletes receive state awards |url=http://en.itar-tass.com/sochi-2014-winter-olympics-and-paralympics/720678 |agency=ITAR-TASS |accessdate=27 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305142408/http://en.itar-tass.com/sochi-2014-winter-olympics-and-paralympics/720678 |archivedate=5 March 2014 }}</ref> Sotnikova did not participate in the 2014 World Championships held in Saitama, Japan.\n\n===2014\u20132015 season===\nSotnikova was selected to compete at [[2014 Rostelecom Cup]] and [[2014 NHK Trophy]]<ref name=1415gp>{{cite web|url=http://isuprod.blob.core.windows.net/media/156252/gp_ladies_updated-july-18.pdf |title=2014\u201315 ISU Grand Prix of Figure Skating |date=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140722053510/http://isuprod.blob.core.windows.net/media/156252/gp_ladies_updated-july-18.pdf |archivedate=22 July 2014 }}</ref> but withdrew due to a torn ankle ligament.<ref name=cbc201411>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=9 November 2014 |title=Adelina Sotnikova to miss rest of ISU Grand Prix due to injury |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/figureskating/adelina-sotnikova-to-miss-rest-of-isu-grand-prix-due-to-injury-1.2829393 |newspaper=[[CBC Sports]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Zaccardi |first=Nick |date=9 November 2014 |title=Adelina Sotnikova out for Grand Prix series with torn ankle ligament |url=http://olympictalk.nbcsports.com/2014/11/09/adelina-sotnikova-ankle-ligament-tear-figure-skating-olympics/ |newspaper=[[NBC Sports]] |accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref> She later withdrew from the [[2015 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2015 Russian Championships]].<ref name=Normal>{{cite news |last=Zaccardi |first=Nick |date=18 December 2014 |title=Adelina Sotnikova to miss Russia Figure Skating Championships |url=http://olympictalk.nbcsports.com/2014/12/18/adelina-sotnikova-to-miss-russia-figure-skating-championships/ |newspaper=[[NBC Sports]] |accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> While doctors had forbidden her to jump in full force,<ref>[Google translation of [[Interfax]] article: https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.interfax.ru%2Frussia%2F420983&sandbox=1 {original Russian: http://www.interfax.ru/russia/420983} {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220212/http://www.interfax.ru/russia/420983%7D |date=3 March 2016 }}]</ref> Adelina Sotnikova decided to focus on the choreographic component in appearances with [[Gleb Savchenko]]<ref>[http://web.icenetwork.com/news/2015/03/05/111032480/savchenko-out-to-make-sotnikova-champion-again icenetwork.com \u2013 Savchenko out to make Sotnikova champion again; Smoldering dancer partners Olympic gold medalist.]</ref>  in the 2015 [[Dancing with the Stars#Russia|Russian version]] of [[Dancing with the Stars]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JgZl-N_2N68 _available video of the two remarkable performers in this event]</ref>\n\n=== 2015\u20132016 season ===\nSotnikova placed 4th in the individual competition of [[Japan Open (figure skating)|Japan Open]].  She appeared at two [[2015\u201316 ISU Challenger Series|Challenger Series]] events, winning the silver medal at the [[2015 Mordovian Ornament]] behind [[Anna Pogorilaya]] and placing 6th at the [[2015 Golden Spin of Zagreb]]. On the [[ISU Grand Prix]], Sotnikova competed only at [[2015 Rostelecom Cup]], and won bronze medal behind her teammates [[Elena Radionova]] and [[Evgenia Medvedeva]].\n\nOn 24\u201327 December 2015, Sotnikova competed at the [[2016 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2016 Russian Championships]] and placed 6th. She was named only as an alternate for the [[2016 European Figure Skating Championships|2016 European Championships]].\n\n=== From 2016 to March 2020 ===\n\nAs injuries started to linger, Sotnikova did not participate at any event, domestic and international, from 2016 onwards. In April 2017, she changed coach and training location, by hiring former Olympic men's champion [[Evgeni Plushenko]] at his skating academy, Angels of Plushenko in [[Moscow]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Yevgeni Plushenko to coach Adelina Sotnikova|url=https://olympics.nbcsports.com/2017/04/04/evgeni-plushenko-adelina-sotnikova-coach/|date=4 April 2017}}</ref> But her persisting health problems prevented her to perform at any competition.\n\nWhile doing a skating show in Turkey, during the summer of 2019, Sotnikova experienced back pain, but thought that it was manageable. However, just prior to the [[2019 Rostelecom Cup]] Exhibition Gala, her spine pain persisted to the point she was considering consulting for further treatment. In December, facing more serious pain, she was recommended to going through immediate surgery, which she preferred to hold it for some time, due to ongoing commitments, including performances of Plushenko's New Year show as [[Cinderella]]. In late February, she underwent surgery, in which she got two spinal implants connected by a metal sheet, itself fixed by six titanium screws inserted into the vertebrae.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spinal implants & titanium screws: Sochi Olympic champion figure skater Adelina Sotnikova announces retirement following surgery|url=https://www.rt.com/sport/482098-adelina-sotnikova-surgery-retirement/|date=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 March 2020, Sotnikova officially announced her retirement from competitive figure skating.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adelina Sotnikova retires from figure skating competition|url=https://olympics.nbcsports.com/2020/03/01/adelina-sotnikova-retires-figure-skating/|date=1 March 2020}}</ref> She plans however, thanks to her surgery, to perform skating shows in the near future.\n\n==Personal life==\nSotnikova was born on 1 July 1996 in Moscow.<ref name=FSRbio/> Her father, Dmitry, is a police officer and her mother, Olga, has worked as a homemaker and in merchandising.<ref name=SD1404/> Her sister, Maria, is two years younger and has [[Treacher Collins syndrome]].<ref name=SD1404/> Sotnikova credits Maria as the most influential person on her career and sees figure skating as a job to support her sister.<ref name=MN130423/><ref name=sochi2014bio/><ref>{{cite web|last=Hersh|first=Phillip|title=Olympics: Russia's Sotnikova golden at home|url=http://www.southbendtribune.com/sports/olympics/olympics-russia-s-sotnikova-golden-at-home/article_aff1f50c-9ae1-11e3-becc-0017a43b2370.html?mode=jqm|publisher=Southbend Tribune|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> Sotnikova attended a high school where athletes form about half the student body.<ref name=absk130314/> In 2013, she enrolled in a sports university with a view to becoming a coach.<ref name=absk130314/><ref name=gs130907/>\n\nIn 2015, Sotnikova started up a beauty salon called \"Studio Be Happy\" in [[Moscow]], which was rebranded as \"Studio Adelina Sotnikova\" by mid-July 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/_studio_as/|title=\u0421\u0442\u0443\u0434\u0438\u044f \u0410\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043d\u044b \u0421\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 (@_studio_as) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos}}</ref>\n\n==Programs==\n[[File:Korea Kim Yuna Free Sochi 12.jpg|right|thumb|200px|17 years old Sotnikova at the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] podium]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Season\n! [[Short program (figure skating)|Short program]]\n! [[Free skating]]\n! Exhibition\n|-\n! 2016\u201317\n|\n* Suite Festiva <br> {{small|choreo. by [[Peter Tchernyshev]]}}\n|\n* Never Meant to Belong <br> {{small|choreo. by [[Peter Tchernyshev]]}}\n|\n|-\n! 2015\u201316\n|\n* [[Historia de un Amor]]\n* Latin Selection <br>{{small|choreo. by Irina Tagaeva and [[Peter Tchernyshev]]}}\n| \n* [[Je suis malade (song)|Je suis malade]] <br> <small> by [[Lara Fabian]]</small><br>{{small|choreo. by Irina Tagaeva}}\n|\n* \"[[Swan Lake]]\" theme <br> <small> performed by David Garrett</small>\n|-\n! 2014\u201315  <br> <ref name=bio1314/>\n|\n* \"[[Swan Lake]]\" theme <br> <small> performed by David Garrett</small>\n|\n* [[Je suis malade (song)|Je suis malade]] <br> <small> by [[Lara Fabian]]</small>\n|\n|-\n! 2013\u201314 <br> <ref